==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shop
<hw>Shop</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>shoppe</ets>,
<ets>schoppe</ets>, AS. <ets>sceoppa</ets> a treasury, a storehouse,
stall, booth; akin to <ets>scypen</ets> a shed, LG. <ets>schup</ets> a
shed, G. <ets>schoppen</ets>, <ets>schuppen</ets>, a shed, a coachhouse,
OHG. <ets>scopf</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A building or an
apartment in which goods, wares, drugs, etc., are sold by
retail.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From <qex>shop</qex> to <qex>shop</qex>⟦br⟧
Wandering, and littering with unfolded silks⟦br⟧
The polished counter.</q> <rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A building in which mechanics or artisans work;
<as>as, a shoe <ex>shop</ex>; a car <ex>shop</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A tailor called me in his <qex>shop</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A person's occupation, business, profession, or the
like, as a subject of attention, interest, conversation, etc.; --
sometimes in deprecation or disapproval; <as>as, to talk <ex>shop</ex>
at a party</as>. Also used attributively, as in <ex>shop
talk</ex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A place where any industry is carried on; <as>as, a
chemist's <ex>shop</ex></as>;</def> also, <fld>(Slang)</fld>, <def>any
of the various places of business which are commonly called offices, as
of a lawyer, doctor, broker, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Any place of resort, as one's house, a restaurant,
etc.</def> <mark>[Slang, Chiefly Eng.]</mark></p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>the group of workers and the activities controlled
by an administrator; <as>as, to have five people in one's
<ex>shop</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Shop</xex> is often used adjectively or in
composition; as, <xex>shop</xex> rent, or <xex>shop</xex>-rent;
<xex>shop thief</xex>, <xex>or shop</xex>-thief; <xex>shop</xex> window,
or <xex>shop</xex>-window, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To smell of the shop</b></col>, <cd>to indicate too
distinctively one's occupation or profession.</cd> -- <col><b>To talk
shop</b></col>, <cd>to make one's business the topic of social
conversation; also, to use the phrases peculiar to one's
employment.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Store; warehouse. See <er>Store</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Shop
<hw>Shop</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Shopped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shopping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To visit shops for the purpose
of purchasing goods.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was engaged with his mother and some ladies to go
<qex>shopping</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

